🌿 Contemplative Reflection

The scriptures are not mirrors for examining other people.

They are mirrors placed before our own heart.

When we misuse scripture to measure the faults of others, its light becomes dim within us.

When we allow scripture to expose our own ego, attachment, pride and misunderstanding, it becomes living wisdom.

That is why every great teacher represented here completes the same journey from a different doorway.

Acharya Jayprakash Ji teaches the purity of sāttvika tapas.

Swami Ashokanand Ji reveals the freedom of the actionless Self.

Muralidhar Acharya Ji points to the indivisible Reality that alone exists.

Anil Kumar Sharma Ji reminds us that true discernment ends in satsanga, where ignorance quietly dissolves.

Together they do not offer four different teachings.

They reveal one continuous path.

Purify the body.

Refine speech.

Quiet the mind.

Abandon doership.

Recognize the Witness.

Abide as Brahman.

This is the pilgrimage of Vedānta.

This is the silent flowering of the Bhagavad Gītā.

This is the living wisdom of the saints.

May we never use scripture to become judges of others.

May we use scripture to become transparent before Truth.

May our study become contemplation.

May contemplation become direct vision.

May direct vision become effortless compassion toward all beings.

॥ श्री राम जय राम जय जय राम ॥

With deepest gratitude to all the revered Mahatmas whose words continue to illuminate the timeless path of Self-Knowledge.

